\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Functions, Morphisms, and Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Functions on Affine Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety.
 We call
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A(X):=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/\mathbf{I}(X)
\]

\end_inset

the 
\series bold
coordinate ring 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The quotient field 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
field of rational functions 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
By an 
\series bold
affine variety 
\series default
we mean an algebraic set which is irreducible.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(X)$
\end_inset

 is a prime ideal (since 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible), hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

 is well-defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{regular}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in X$
\end_inset

 be a point.
 We call 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X,p}:=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in A(X)\text{ and }g(p)\neq0\right\} \subset K(X)
\]

\end_inset

the 
\series bold
local ring 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is a non-empty open subset, we set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X}(U):=\bigcap_{p\in U}O_{X,p}\subset K(X).
\]

\end_inset

This is a subring of 
\begin_inset Formula $K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 We call this the 
\series bold
ring of regular functions 
\series default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{X,p}:=\{f\in A(X)\mid f(p)=0\}$
\end_inset

 of all functions that vanish at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a maximal ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

.
 With this definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 is just the localization of the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

 at the maximal ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}_{X,p}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A(X)$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 be the open subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f):=\{p\in X\mid f(p)\neq0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Open subsets of this form are called 
\series bold
distinguished open subsets
\series default
.
 They form a basis in the Zariski topology.
 In fact, every open set can be written as a finite union of distinguished
 open subsets.
 Also, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f_{2})$
\end_inset

 are two distinguished open subsets for two distinct polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f_{1})\cap D(f_{2})=D(f_{1}f_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

It may be tempting to think that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in A(X)\text{ and }g(p)\neq0\text{ for all }p\in U\right\} ,
\]

\end_inset

but this is not necessarily the case.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{4}$
\end_inset

 be the variety defined by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}x_{4}=x_{2}x_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}$
\end_inset

 is defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{2})$
\end_inset

 and the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}$
\end_inset

 is defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{4})$
\end_inset

.
 By the equation of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, these two functions coincide where they are both defined; in other words
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}=\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}\in K(X).
\]

\end_inset

So this gives rise to a regular function on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{2})\cup D(x_{4})$
\end_inset

, but there is no representation of this function as a quotient of two polynomia
ls in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4}]$
\end_inset

 that works on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{2})\cup D(x_{4})$
\end_inset

; we have to use different representations at different points.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, it can be the case that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X}(U)=\left\{ \frac{f}{g}\mid f,g\in A(X)\text{ and }g(p)\neq0\text{ for all }p\in U\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{C}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 We may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 share no common factors.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not a constant, then there exists another point 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}(q)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,q}$
\end_inset

, we must be able to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 However, the only way we can have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}=\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}}
\]

\end_inset

is if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=hf_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}=hf_{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is some polynomial.
 But this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(q)=h(q)f_{2}(q)=0$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Later on we will show how the failure of this regular function to be represented
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

globally
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is measured by cohomology.
 In particular we will find that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}\right)$
\end_inset

 represents a nontrivial element in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(x_{2},x_{4};A(X))$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}(x_{2},x_{4};A(X))$
\end_inset

 is the first cohomology in the stable Koszul complex given below: 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[ ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

0 
\backslash
arrow{r} 
\backslash
&  O_X (D(x_2 ) 
\backslash
cup D(x_4 )) 
\backslash
arrow{rr}{
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
begin{matrix} O_X (D(x_2 ) ) 
\backslash

\backslash
 
\backslash
bigoplus 
\backslash

\backslash
 O_X (D(x_4 ) ) 
\backslash
end{matrix} 
\backslash
arrow{rr}{ 
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} 1 
\backslash

\backslash
 -1 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& O_X (D(x_2 ) 
\backslash
cap D(x_4 ) ) 
\backslash
arrow{r} 
\backslash
& 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Indeed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is in the kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{smallmatrix}1\\
-1
\end{smallmatrix}\right)$
\end_inset

 since both 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}$
\end_inset

 restrict to the same function on 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x_{2})\cap D(x_{4})$
\end_inset

.
 That 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{x_{1}}{x_{2}},\frac{x_{3}}{x_{4}}\right)$
\end_inset

 is not in the image of a function in 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(D(x_{2})\cup D(x_{4}))$
\end_inset

 is precisely saying that no representation of this function as a quotient
 of two polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},x_{4}]$
\end_inset

.
 The most important thing to take away from this example is that elements
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 are described 
\emph on
locally
\emph default
.
 Indeed, let's spell out what it means for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,p_{1}}\cap O_{X,p_{2}}$
\end_inset

: Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,p_{1}}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{f_{1}}{g_{1}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}(p_{1})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,p_{2}}$
\end_inset

, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{2}(p_{2})\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f_{1}}{g_{1}}=\varphi=\frac{f_{2}}{g_{2}}\in K(X).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Something analagous happens in Algebraic Number Theory.
 When studying algebraic number fields, one finds that most rings of integers
 are not UFDs.
 For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 with ring of integers being 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{K}=\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 An example of where unique factorization fails is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\cdot3=(1-\sqrt{-5})(1+\sqrt{-5}$
\end_inset

).
 We can also think of this as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2}{1+\sqrt{-5}}=\frac{1-\sqrt{-5}}{3}\in K.
\]

\end_inset

It turns out that we can measure this using cohomology as well.
 In Algebraic Number Theory, it's called the class group.
 In this case, we introduce an equivalence relation on the set of fractional
 ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{K}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}\sim\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{a}=\gamma\mathfrak{b}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\in K$
\end_inset

.
 The class group measures the number of equivalence classes.
 For instance, the the prime ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle2,1+\sqrt{-5}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle3,1-\sqrt{-5}\rangle$
\end_inset

 represent the same equivalence class since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma\langle2,1+\sqrt{-5}\rangle=\langle3,1-\sqrt{-5}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{1-\sqrt{-5}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmaregularfuncitonsheaf}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following definition of regular functions is equivalent to the one
 of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Definition~(
\backslash
ref{regular})
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be an open subset of an affine variety 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:U\to K$
\end_inset

 is called regular at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 if there is a neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that there are polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)=\frac{f(q)}{g(q)}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in V$
\end_inset

.
 It is called regular on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 if it is regular at every point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is obvious that an element of the ring of regular functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 determines a regular function in the sense of the lemma.
 Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in O_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a point in 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $r\in O_{X}\subset O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

 implies that it can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $r=\frac{f}{g}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V:=D(g)\cap U$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in A(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, we are done.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:U\to\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be a regular funciton in the sense of the lemma.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U$
\end_inset

 be any point.
 Then there are polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(q)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)=\frac{f(q)}{g(q)}$
\end_inset

 for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in some neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}\in K(X)$
\end_inset

 is the element in the ring of regular functions that we seek.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In fact, all we have to show is that this element does not depend on the
 choices that we made.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\in U$
\end_inset

 be another point (not necessarily distinct from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

), and suppose that there are polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f',g'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}=\frac{f'}{g'}$
\end_inset

 on some neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $fg'=gf'$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 and hence on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cap V'$
\end_inset

 is dense in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (every open set is dense in an irreducible topological space).
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $fg'-gf'\in I(X)$
\end_inset

, so it is zero in 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}=\frac{f'}{g'}\in K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X}(D(f))=A(X)_{f}:=\left\{ \frac{g}{f^{r}}\mid g\in A(X)\text{ and }r\geq0\right\} .
\]

\end_inset

In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(X)=A(X)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 any regular function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is polynomial (take 
\begin_inset Formula $f=1$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)_{f}\subset O_{X}(D(f))$
\end_inset

, so let us prove the converse.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X}(D(f))\subset K(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\{g\in A(X)\mid g\varphi\in A(X)\}$
\end_inset

.
 This is an ideal in 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X);$
\end_inset

 we want to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{r}\in J$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, for then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{r}\varphi=h$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in A(X)$
\end_inset

, and we'd have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{h}{f^{r}}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason we work with ideals is because our argument will use Nullstellensatz
 which is a theorem about ideals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in D(f)$
\end_inset

, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{h}{g}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\neq0$
\end_inset

 in a neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in J$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 contains an element not vanishing at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is arbitrary, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(\widetilde{J})\subset\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{I}(X)+\widetilde{f})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 is a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{J}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse image of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 under the natural quotient map 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]\to A(X)$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(\mathbf{V}(\mathbf{I}(X)+\widetilde{f}))\subset\mathbf{I}(\mathbf{V}(\widetilde{J}))$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in\mathbf{I}(\mathbf{V}(\widetilde{J}))$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}^{r}\in\widetilde{J}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 by Nullstellensatz, and so 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{r}\in J$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that we needed to use Nullstellensatz here.
 In fact, the statement is false if the ground field is not algebraically
 closed, as you can see from the example of the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{x^{2}+1}$
\end_inset

 that is regular on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

, but not polynomial.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example2.1.12}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Probably the easiest case of an open subset of an affine variety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 that is not of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 is the complement 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{C}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

 of the origin in the affine plane.
 Let us compute 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{\mathbb{C}^{2}}(U)$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, any element 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{\mathbb{C}^{2}}(U)\subset\mathbb{C}(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
globally 
\emph default
the quotient 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{f}{g}$
\end_inset

 of two 
\emph on
polynomials
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in\mathbb{C}[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
 The condition we have to satisfy is that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a,b)\neq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\neq(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 To understand why this is the case, pick 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\neq(0,0)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Let's be sure that there is not another representation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

: Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

 for two other polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q\in\mathbb{C}[x,y]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $q(a,b)\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}=\frac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)q(a,b)=p(a,b)g(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q(a,b)\neq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is field, we must therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So what we've shown here is that in order for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{f}{g}\in O_{\mathbb{C}^{2},(a,b)}$
\end_inset

, we need either 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a,b)\neq0$
\end_inset

 or if 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

.
 to make sense, we'd need 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(g)\subset\mathbf{V}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a,b)=0$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a,b)q(a,b)=p(a,b)g(a,b)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{f}{g}=\frac{p}{q},
\]

\end_inset

which implies .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim that this implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We know already by the Nullstellensatz that there is no non-constant polynomial
 that has empty zero locus in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

, so we can assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 vanishes on 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 If we write 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x,y)=f_{0}(x)+f_{1}(x)y+f_{2}(x)y^{2}+\cdots+f_{n}(x)y^{n},
\]

\end_inset

this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}(x)$
\end_inset

 must be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{m}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 In fact:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the zero polynomial, the 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 contains 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as a factor and hence the whole 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis in its zero locus,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 contains more than one monomial, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 has a zero 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\neq0$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x_{0},0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,y)$
\end_inset

 is of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(x,y)=x^{m}+f_{1}(x)y+f_{2}(x)y^{2}+\cdots+f_{n}(x)y^{n}.
\]

\end_inset

Now set 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 for some small 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,0)=x^{m}$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 are continuous, the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 cannot be the zero or a constant polynomial.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x,\varepsilon)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for some 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, which is a contradiction.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be an integral domain.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 This means that the map from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 given by multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the map from 
\begin_inset Formula $S/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 given by multiplication by 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both injective.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}}=\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then this implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=hg_{1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in S$
\end_inset

 .
 Hence,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & =f_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1}\\
 & =hg_{1}g_{2}-f_{2}g_{1}\\
 & =g_{1}(hg_{2}-f_{2}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=hg_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}}=\frac{f_{1}}{f_{2}}=\frac{hg_{1}}{hg_{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what we've shown is that if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then there are no nontrivial ways of writing 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{g_{1}}{g_{2}}$
\end_inset

: they are all of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{hg_{1}}{hg_{2}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

When does 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 fail to form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

? Well, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, so the map from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 given by multiplication of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
 The only place where it can fail is if the map from 
\begin_inset Formula $S/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $S/g_{1}$
\end_inset

 given by multiplication of 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{g}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
 This means that there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}g_{2}=f_{2}g_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 is not of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $hg_{1}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in S$
\end_inset

.
 At the same time, this also implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},f_{2}$
\end_inset

 fails to form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as well.
 This pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},f_{2})$
\end_inset

 represents a nontrivial element in 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(g_{1},g_{2};S)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}(g_{1},g_{2};S)$
\end_inset

 is the first homology in the Koszul complex 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{K}(g_{1},g_{2};S)_{\bullet}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{center}
\backslash
begin{tikzcd}[ampersand replacement=
\backslash
&] 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
mathcal{K}(g_1 , g_2 ; S )_{
\backslash
bullet }:  
\backslash
& 0 
\backslash
arrow{r} 
\backslash
& S 
\backslash
arrow{rr}{
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} g_2 
\backslash

\backslash
 -g_1  
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& S^2 
\backslash
arrow{rr}{
\backslash
begin{pmatrix} g_1 & g_2 
\backslash
end{pmatrix} } 
\backslash
& 
\backslash
& S 
\backslash
arrow{r} 
\backslash
& 0 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{tikzcd}
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $I=\langle g_{1},g_{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 The maximal length 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 of an 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{r}\in I$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

-
\series bold
depth 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 We denote this by 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{depth}(I,S)$
\end_inset

.
 One can show that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mbox{depth}(I,M)=2-\mbox{sup}\{i\mid H_{i}(g_{1},g_{2};S)\neq0\}.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is an integral domain, we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}(g_{1},g_{2};S)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, if 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1},g_{2}$
\end_inset

 fail to form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{depth}(I,M)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For instance, let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{Q}(\sqrt{-5})$
\end_inset

 with ring of integers being 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{K}=\mathbb{Z}[\sqrt{-5}]$
\end_inset

.
 The sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $2,1+\sqrt{-5}$
\end_inset

 does not form a regular sequence in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}_{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\cdot3=(1+\sqrt{-5})(1-\sqrt{-5})
\]

\end_inset

and neither 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\sqrt{-5}$
\end_inset

 nor 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\sqrt{-5}$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}=\langle2,1+\sqrt{-5}\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{q}=\langle3,1-\sqrt{-5}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2}{1+\sqrt{-5}}=\frac{1-\sqrt{-5}}{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We have seen that regular functions on affine varieties are defined in terms
 of local properties: they are set-theoretic functions that can locally
 be written as quotients of polynomials.
 Local constructions of function-like objects occur in many places in algebraic
 geometry (and also in many other 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

topological
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fields of mathematics), so we should formalize the ideal of such objects.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
presheaf 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of rings on a topological space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 assigns to each open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, and to every pair of nested open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, a ring homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{U}^{V}:\mathcal{F}(V)\to\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
restriction map
\series default
, such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{U}^{U}$
\end_inset

 is the identity map for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{U}^{V}\circ\mathcal{F}_{V}^{W}=\mathcal{F}_{U}^{W}$
\end_inset

 for all open sets 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset V\subset W$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
sections
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

; elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(X)$
\end_inset

 are called 
\series bold
global sections
\series default
.
 The restriction maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{U}^{V}$
\end_inset

 are written as 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mapsto f\mid_{U}$.

\end_inset

 A presheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of rings is called a 
\series bold
sheaf 
\series default
of rings if it satisfies the following glueing property: if 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is an open set, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 ,and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\in\mathcal{F}(U_{i})$
\end_inset

 are sections for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\mid_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=f_{j}\mid_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

, then there is a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\mid U_{i}}=f_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Presheaves that are not Sheaves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 be the presheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 defined as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}(U)=\begin{cases}
\mathbb{Q} & \text{if}U=\mathbb{R}\\
\mathbb{Z} & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
locally, this presheaf is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0\}$
\end_inset

, so where did this extra element 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 come from? It can't be a sheaf.
 It would, however, be a sheaf if we got rid of the element 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 be the presheaf of continuous bounded functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Why is this not a sheaf? Hint: Try gluing a bunch of continuous bounded
 functions to form a continuous unbounded function on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We can turn this thing into a sheaf if we adjoin continuous unbounded functions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{Note:}$
\end_inset

 Notice in the previous two examples we either needed to remove elements
 to turn a presheaf into a sheaf, or we needed to adjoin elements to turn
 a presheaf into a sheaf.
 This process of removing or adjoining elements of a presheaf to obtain
 a sheaf is known as 
\begin_inset Formula $\textbf{sheafification}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety, then the rings 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 of regular functions on open subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (with the obvious restriction maps 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(V)\to O_{X}(U)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset V$
\end_inset

) form a sheaf of rings 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}$
\end_inset

, called the 
\series bold
sheaf of regular functions 
\series default
or 
\series bold
structure sheaf 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, all defining properties of presheaves are obvious, and the glueing
 property of sheaves is easily seen from the description of regular functions
 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemmaregularfuncitonsheaf})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here are some examples from other fields of Mathematics: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and for any open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 be the ring of continuous functions on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 Together with the obvious restriction maps, these rings 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 form a sheaf, the 
\series bold
sheaf of continuous functions
\series default
.
 In the same way we can define the sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 times differentiable functions, analytic functions, holomorphic functions
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and so on.
 The same definitions can be applied if 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a real or complex manifold instead of just 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In all these examples, the sheaves just defined 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

are
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 precisely the functions that are considered to be morphisms in the correspondin
g category (for example, in complex analysis the morphisms are just the
 holomorphic maps).
 This is usually expressed in the following way: a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,\mathcal{F})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a topological space and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of rings on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
ringed space
\series default
.
 The sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is then called the structure sheaf of this ringed space.
 (Although being general, this terminology will usually only be applied
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 actually has an interpretation as the space of functions that are considered
 to be morphisms in the corresponding category.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a topological space, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in X$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 a (pre-)sheaf on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Consider pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is an open neighborhood of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in\mathcal{F}(U)$
\end_inset

 a section of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 We call two such pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(U',\varphi')$
\end_inset

 equivalent if there is an open neighborhood 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subset U\cap U'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\mid_{V}=\varphi\mid_{V}$
\end_inset

.
 The set of all such pairs modulo this equivalence relation is called the
 
\series bold
stalk 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{p}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, its elements are called 
\series bold
germs 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,O_{X})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(Y,O_{Y})$
\end_inset

 be ringed spaces whose structure sheaves 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{Y}$
\end_inset

 are sheaves of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued functions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a set-theoretic map.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi:U\to k$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued function on an open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, the composition 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\circ f$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(U)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is again a set-theoretic function.
 It is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\varphi$
\end_inset

 and is called the 
\series bold
pull-back 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
morphism 
\series default
if it is continuous, and if it pulls back regular functions to regular functions
, i.e.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}O_{Y}(U)\subset O_{X}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 for all open 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now want to show that for affine varieties, the situation is a lot easier:
 we actually do not have to deal with open subsets, but it suffices to check
 the pull-back property on 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
functions only:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma2.3.4}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be a continuous map between affine varieties.
 Then the following are equivalent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 pulls back regular functions on open subsets to regular functions on open
 subsets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{Y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\varphi\in O_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 pulls back 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
regular functions to 
\emph on
global 
\emph default
regular functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in X$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{Y,f(p)}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\varphi\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 pulls back germs of regular functions to germs of regular functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1)
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

(2): Trivial
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3)
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

(1): Follows immediately from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{Y}(U)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}(f^{-1}(U))$
\end_inset

 as intersections of local rings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2)
\begin_inset Formula $\implies$
\end_inset

(3): Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\in O_{Y,f(p)}$
\end_inset

 be the germ of a regular function on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\frac{g}{h}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g,h\in A(Y)=O_{Y}(Y)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f(p))\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 By (2), 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}h$
\end_inset

 are global regular functions in 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)=O_{X}(X)$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}\varphi=\frac{f^{*}g}{f^{*}h}\in O_{X,p}$
\end_inset

, since we have 
\begin_inset Formula $h(f(p))\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the affine line with coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be the affine line with coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the set-theoretic map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:X\to Y,\qquad x\mapsto y=x^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that this is a morphism.
 In fact, by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.4})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we just need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 pulls back polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[y]$
\end_inset

 to polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

.
 But this is obvious, as the pull-back of a polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(y)\in k[y]$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x^{2})$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 we substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

).
 This is still a polynomial, so it is in 
\begin_inset Formula $k[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Polynomial Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be affine varieties.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
polynomial mapping 
\series default
(or 
\series bold
regular mapping
\series default
) if there exist polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1},\dots,f_{n}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(a_{1},\dots,a_{m})=(f_{1}(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}),\dots,f_{n}(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{m})\in X$
\end_inset

.
 We say that the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple of polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})\in(K[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}])^{n}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
represents 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the 
\series bold
components 
\series default
of this representation.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem1}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial mapping from 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{m}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 means that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}),\dots,f_{n}(a_{1},\dots,a_{m}))$
\end_inset

 must satisfy the defining equations of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 for all points 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{1},\dots,a_{m})\in X$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Of particular interest is the case 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbb{A}_{K}^{1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 simply becomes a scalar 
\series bold
polynomial function
\series default
 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A polynomial map from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the Zariski topology.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $D(g)$
\end_inset

 is a basic open set in 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(D(g))=D(f^{*}g)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is continuous and pulls back polynomials to polynomials, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.4})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a morphism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let's go over some examples of polynomial mappings.
 We typically use 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v,w$
\end_inset

 to denote coordinate functions, 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta,\gamma$
\end_inset

 to denote numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p,q$
\end_inset

 to denote points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathbf{V}(y-x^{2},z-x^{3})$
\end_inset

 be the twisted cubic in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\left\{ (a,b,c)\in K^{3}\mid b=a^{2}\text{ and }c=a^{3}\right\} .
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\mathbf{V}(v-u-u^{2})$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\left\{ (\alpha,\beta)\in K^{2}\mid\beta=\alpha+\alpha^{2}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to describe a polynomial map from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 be given by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,c)\in X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $(ab,a^{2}b^{2}+c):=(\alpha,\beta)\in Y$
\end_inset

 is such a map.
 We need to make sure that this is well-defined.
 In particular, we need to check that the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

 really does belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 We verify this by showing that the point satisfies the defining equation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: Indeed, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c-ab=0$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b,c)\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z-xy\in\langle y-x^{2},z-x^{3}\rangle$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(v-u-u^{2})(\alpha,\beta) & =\alpha-\beta-\beta^{2}\\
 & =(c+a^{2}b^{2})-(ab)-(ab)^{2}\\
 & =c-ab\\
 & =0.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is indeed a polynomial map from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},f_{2})$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1} & =xy\\
f_{2} & =x^{2}y^{2}+z.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe that the map 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 induces a map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{*}:K[u,v]/\langle v-u-u^{2}\rangle\to K[x,y,z]/\langle y-x^{2},z-x^{3}\rangle,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra map induced by mapping
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u & \mapsto xy\\
v & \mapsto x^{2}y^{2}+z
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We give some more examples of morphisms of affine algebraic sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\to V(T_{2}-T_{1}^{2})\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}(k)$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto(x^{2},x)$
\end_inset

, is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 It is even an isomorphism with inverse morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\mapsto y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)\to V(T_{2}^{2}-T_{1}^{2}(T_{1}+1))$
\end_inset

, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto(x^{2}-1,x(x^{2}-1))$
\end_inset

, is a morphism of affine algebraic sets.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(k)\neq2$
\end_inset

, it is not bijective: 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 are both mapped to the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{char}(k)=2$
\end_inset

, it is bijective but not an isomorphism.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We identify the space 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $(n\times n)$
\end_inset

-matrices with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n^{2}}(k)$
\end_inset

, thus giving 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 the structure of an affine algebraic set.
 Then sending a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in M_{n}(k)$
\end_inset

 to its determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}(A)$
\end_inset

 is a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{n}(k)\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(k)$
\end_inset

 of affine algebraic sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, consider the exponential function 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{exp}:\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})\to\mathbb{A}^{1}(\mathbb{C})$
\end_inset

.
 This is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
a morphism of algebraic sets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\mathbb{A}_{K}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x_{1},\dots,x_{m}]$
\end_inset

 represent the same polynomial function on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in\mathbf{I}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{1},\dots,g_{n})$
\end_inset

 represent the same polynomial mapping from 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}_{K}^{n}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}-g_{i}\in\mathbf{I}(V)$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g=h\in\mathbf{I}(V)$
\end_inset

, then for any point 
\begin_inset Formula $p=(a_{1},\dots,a_{m})\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)-g(p)=h(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 represent the same function on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 represent the same function, then, at every 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)-g(p)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in\mathbf{I}(V)$
\end_inset

 by definition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Follows directly from (1).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma2.3.7}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{A}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be affine varieties.
 There is a one-to-one correspondence between morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:A(Y)\to A(X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Any morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 determines a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:O_{Y}(Y)=A(Y)\to O_{X}(X)=A(X)$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Conversely, if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi:K[y_{1},\dots,y_{m}]/\mathbf{I}(Y)\to K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/\mathbf{I}(X)
\]

\end_inset

is any 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism, then it determines a polynomial map 
\begin_inset Formula $f=(f_{1},\dots,f_{m}):X\to Y$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}=\varphi(y_{i})$
\end_inset

, and hence a morphism.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
isomorphism 
\series default
is defined to be a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to Y$
\end_inset

 that has an inverse, i.e.
 a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $g:Y\to X$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\text{id}_{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\circ g=\text{id}_{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Warning
\series default
: An isomorphism of affine varieties is 
\emph on
not 
\emph default
the same as a bijective morphism.
 For example, let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{2}$
\end_inset

 be the curve given by the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}=y^{3}$
\end_inset

 and consider the map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\mathbb{A}^{1}\to X\qquad t\mapsto(t^{3},t^{2}).
\]

\end_inset

This is a morphism as it is given by polynomials, and it is bijective as
 the inverse is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:X\to\mathbb{A}^{1}\qquad(x,y)\mapsto\begin{cases}
\frac{x}{y} & \text{if }(x,y)\neq(0,0),\\
0 & \text{if }(x,y)=(0,0).
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

But if 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 was an isomorphism, the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K[x,y]/\langle x^{2}-y^{3}\rangle\to K[t]\qquad x\mapsto t^{3}\text{ and }y\mapsto t^{2}
\]

\end_inset

would have to be an isomorphism.
 This is obviously not the case, as the image of this algebra homomorphism
 contains no linear polynomials.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Products of Affine Varieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{A}^{m}$
\end_inset

 be affine varieties with ideals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(X)\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(Y)\subset K[y_{1},\dots,y_{m}]$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
product 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to be the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X\times Y=\{(p,q)\in\mathbb{A}^{n}\times\mathbb{A}^{m}\mid p\in X\text{ and }q\in Y\}\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}\times\mathbb{A}^{m}=\mathbb{A}^{n+m}.
\]

\end_inset

Obviously, this is an algebraic set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n+m}$
\end_inset

, with ideal 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{I}(X\times Y)=\mathbf{I}(X)+\mathbf{I}(Y)\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},y_{1},\dots,y_{m}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are affine varieties, then so is 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For simplicity, let us just write 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for the collection of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 for the collection of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(X\times Y)$
\end_inset

 is prime.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g\in K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 be polynomial functions such that 
\begin_inset Formula $fg\in\mathbf{I}(X\times Y)$
\end_inset

; we have to show that either 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 vanishes on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y\subset\mathbf{V}(f)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y\subset\mathbf{V}(g)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So let us assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y\not\subset\mathbf{V}(f)$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 there is a point 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)\in(X\times Y)\backslash\mathbf{V}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\cdot,q)\in K[x]$
\end_inset

 the polynomial obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in K[x,y]$
\end_inset

 by plugging in the coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 First, we will show that we can find an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U\times Y\subset\mathbf{V}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, this open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 will just be 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))$
\end_inset

: For all 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\in X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))$
\end_inset

 we must have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y\subset\mathbf{V}(f(p',\cdot)g(p',\cdot))=\mathbf{V}(f(p',\cdot))\cup\mathbf{V}(g(p',\cdot)).
\]

\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\not\subset\mathbf{V}(f(p',\cdot))$
\end_inset

 by choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbf{V}(g(p',\cdot))$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

This is true for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p'\in X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))$
\end_inset

 by the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $p'$
\end_inset

, so we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))\times Y\subset\mathbf{V}(g)$
\end_inset

.
 But as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(g)$
\end_inset

 is closed, it must in fact contain the closure of 
\begin_inset Formula $(X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))\times Y$
\end_inset

 as well, which is just 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible and 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash\mathbf{V}(f(\cdot,q))$
\end_inset

 a non-empty open subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The obvious projection maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{X}:X\times Y\to X$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)\mapsto p$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{Y}:X\times Y\to Y$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,q)\mapsto q$
\end_inset

, are given by (trivial) polynomial maps and are therefore morphisms.
 The important main property of the product 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

 is the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 be affine varieties.
 Then the product 
\begin_inset Formula $X\times Y$
\end_inset

 satisfies the following universal property: for every affine variety 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $f:Z\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g:Z\to Y$
\end_inset

, there is a unique morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h:Z\to X\times Y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\pi_{X}\circ h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\pi_{Y}\circ h$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In other words, giving a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to X\times Y$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the same
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as giving two morphisms 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\to Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 Then by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f:Z\to X$
\end_inset

 is given by a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}:K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/\mathbf{I}(X)\to A$
\end_inset

.
 This in turn is determined by giving the images 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}:=f^{*}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 of the generators 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, satisfying the relations of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 The same is true for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, which is determined by the images 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}:=g^{*}(y_{i})\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now it is obvious that the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 determine a 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra homomorphism
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},y_{1},\dots,y_{m}]/(\mathbf{I}(X)+\mathbf{I}(Y))\to A,
\]

\end_inset

which determines a morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $h:Z\to X\times Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

To show uniqueness, just note that the relations 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\pi_{X}\circ h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\pi_{Y}\circ h$
\end_inset

 imply immediately that 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 must be given set-theoretically by 
\begin_inset Formula $h(p)=(f(p),g(p))$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 allows us to associate an affine variety up to isomorphism to any finitely
 generated 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-algebra that is a domain: if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is such an algebra, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 be generators of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $A=K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]/I$
\end_inset

 for some ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the affine variety in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 defined by the ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

; by the lemma it is defined up to isomorphism.
 Therefore we should make a (very minor) redefinition of the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

affine variety
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to allow for objects that are isomorphic to an affine variety in the old
 sense, but that do not come with an intrinsic description as the zero locus
 of some polynomials in affine space:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,O_{X})$
\end_inset

 is called an 
\series bold
affine variety 
\series default
over 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 if 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued functions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to an affine variety.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Here is an example of an affine variety in this new sense, although it is
 not a priori given as the zero locus of some polynomials in affine space:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemma2.3.16}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in A(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Then the ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),O_{X}\mid_{D(f)})$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to an affine variety with coordinate ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subset\mathbb{A}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be an affine variety and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{f}\in K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n}]$
\end_inset

 be a representative of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $J\subset K[x_{1},\dots,x_{n},t]$
\end_inset

 be the ideal generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{I}(X)$
\end_inset

 and the function 
\begin_inset Formula $1-t\widetilde{f}$
\end_inset

.
 We claim that the ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(D(f),O_{X}\mid_{D(f)})$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to the affine variety
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{V}(J)=\left\{ \left(p,\frac{1}{\widetilde{f}(p)}\right)\mid p\in X\right\} \subset\mathbb{A}^{n+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Consider the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi:\mathbf{V}(J)\to X$
\end_inset

 given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(p,\lambda)=p$
\end_inset

.
 This is a morphism with image 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f)$
\end_inset

 and inverse morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{-1}(p)=\left(p,\frac{1}{\widetilde{f}(p)}\right)$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is an isomorphism.
 It is obvious that 
\begin_inset Formula $A(\mathbf{V}(J))=A(X)_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Prevarieties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We have just seen that even open subsets of affine varieties are themselves
 affine varities, provided that the open subset is the complement of the
 zero locus of a single polynomial equation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

On the other hand, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Example~(
\backslash
ref{example2.1.12})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 shows that not all open subsets of affine varieties are themselves isomorphic
 to affine varieties.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\mathbb{C}^{2}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then we've seen that 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{U}(U)=K[x,y]$
\end_inset

.
 So if 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 was an affine variety, its coordinate ring must be 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]$
\end_inset

, which is the same as the coordinate ring of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.7})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

 would have to be isomorphic, with the isomorphism given by the identity
 map.
 Obviously, this is not true.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is not an affine variety.
 It can however be covered by two open subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $D(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D(y)$
\end_inset

, which are both affine by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Lemma~(
\backslash
ref{lemma2.3.16})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This leads us to the idea of
\series bold
\emph on
 
\emph default
patching
\series default
\emph on
 
\emph default
affine varieties together.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Every open subset of an affine variety can be written as a finite union
 of distinguished open subsets.
 Indeed, every closed subset has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})=\mathbf{V}(f_{1})\cap\cdots\cap\mathbf{V}(f_{n})$
\end_inset

, and so every open subset has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $D(f_{1},\dots,f_{n})=D(f_{1})\cup\cdots\cup D(f_{n})$
\end_inset

.
 This leads us to the idea that we should study objects that are not affine
 varieties themselves, but rather can be covered by (finitely many) affine
 varieties.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
prevariety 
\series default
is a ringed space 
\begin_inset Formula $(X,O_{X})$
\end_inset

 such that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is irreducible, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}$
\end_inset

 is a sheaf of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

-valued functions,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
there is a finite open cover 
\begin_inset Formula $\{U_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{i},O_{X}\mid_{U_{i}})$
\end_inset

 is an affine variety for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 of a prevariety such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(U,O_{X}\mid_{U})$
\end_inset

 is isomorphic to an affine variety is called an 
\series bold
affine open set
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As before, a morphism o prevarieties is just a morphism as ringed spaces.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

The most general way to construct prevarieties is to take some affine varieties
 and patch them together: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be prevarieties, 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 be non-empty open subsets, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:(U_{1},O_{X_{1}}\mid_{U_{1}})\to(U_{2},O_{X_{2}}\mid_{U_{2}})$
\end_inset

 be an isomorphism.
 Then we can define a prevariety 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, obtained by 
\series bold
gluing 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 via the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a set, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the disjoint union 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\cup X_{2}$
\end_inset

 modulo the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $p\sim\varphi(p)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a topological space, we endow 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 with the so-called 
\series bold
quotient topology
\series default
 induced by the above equivalence relation, i.e.
 we say that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset X$
\end_inset

 is open if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}^{-1}(U)\subset X_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{2}^{-1}(U)\subset X_{2}$
\end_inset

 are both open, with 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{1}:X_{1}\to X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{2}:X_{2}\to X$
\end_inset

 being the obvious inclusion maps.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As a ringed space, we define the structure sheaf 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{X}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
O_{X}(U)=\{(\varphi_{1},\varphi_{2})\mid\varphi_{1}\in O_{X_{1}}(U\cap X_{1}),\text{ }\varphi_{2}\in O_{X_{2}}(U\cap X_{2}),\text{ and }\varphi_{1}=\varphi_{2}\text{ on the overlap (i.e. }f^{*}(\varphi_{2}\mid_{i_{2}^{-1}(U)\cap U_{2}})=\varphi_{1}\mid_{i_{1}^{-1}(U)\cap U_{1}})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=X_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}=U_{2}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\backslash\{0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 The space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 can be thought of as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\cup\{\infty\}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course the affine line 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}=\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset X$
\end_inset

 sits in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The complement 
\begin_inset Formula $X\backslash X_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a single point that corresponds to the zero point in 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{2}\cong\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and hence to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\infty=\frac{1}{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the coordinate of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case 
\begin_inset Formula $K=\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

, the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is just the Riemann sphere 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}_{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:U_{1}\to U_{2}$
\end_inset

 be the identity map.
 Then the space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 obtained by gluing along 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the affine line with the zero point doubled
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Obviously this is a somewhat weird place.
 Speaking in classical terms, if we have a sequence of points tending to
 the zero, this sequence would have two possible limits, namely the two
 zero points.
 Usually we want to exclude such spaces from the objects we consider.
 In the theory of manifolds, this is simply done by requiring that a manifold
 satisfies the so-called 
\series bold
Hausdorff property
\series default
.
 This is obviously not satisfied for our space 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be the complex affine curve 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}.
\]

\end_inset

We can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactify
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 by adding two points at infinity, corresponding to the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\infty$
\end_inset

 and the two possible values for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 To construct this space rigorously, we construct a prevariety as follows:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If we make the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

, the equation of the curve becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y^{2}\widetilde{x}^{4}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

If we make an additional coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\frac{y}{x^{4}}$
\end_inset

, then this becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x}).
\]

\end_inset

In these coordinates, we can add our two points at infinity, as they now
 correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=0$
\end_inset

 (and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{y}=\pm1$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Summarizing, our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compactified curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is just the prevariety obtained by gluing the two affine varieties
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\{(x,y)\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid y^{2}=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)\}\quad\text{and}\quad\widetilde{X}=\{(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\in\mathbb{C}^{2}\mid\widetilde{y}^{2}=(1-\widetilde{x})(1-2\widetilde{x})(1-3\widetilde{x})(1-4\widetilde{x})\}
\]

\end_inset

along the isomorphism 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:U\to\widetilde{U},\qquad(x,y)\mapsto(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})=\left(\frac{1}{x},\frac{y}{x^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}:\widetilde{U}\to U,\qquad(\widetilde{x},\widetilde{y})\mapsto(x,y)=\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}},\frac{\widetilde{y}}{\widetilde{x}^{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{x\neq0\}\subset X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{U}=\{\widetilde{x}\neq0\}\subset\widetilde{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{P}^{1}\to\mathbb{A}^{1}$
\end_inset

 be a morphism.
 We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 must be constant.
 In fact, consider the restriction 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{\mathbb{A}^{1}}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to the open affine subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{A}^{1}\subset\mathbb{P}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, the restriction of a morphism is again a morphism, so 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{\mathbb{A}^{1}}$
\end_inset

 must be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto y=p(x)$
\end_inset

 for some polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in K[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider the second patch of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}^{1}$
\end_inset

 with coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}=\frac{1}{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying this coordinate change, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\mid_{\mathbb{P}^{1}\backslash\{0\}}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}\mapsto p\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But this must be a morphism too, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\frac{1}{\widetilde{x}}\right)$
\end_inset

 must be a polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{x}$
\end_inset

.
 This is only tru if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a constant.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
